Note:
Darwin ARM64 (Apple Silicon) System Call Implementation

This file implements BSD-style system calls for macOS / iOS / iPadOS on
Apple Silicon (M1, M2, M3, M4 and later) and other Apple-designed ARM64
SoCs (A14 Bionic onwards in iPhones and iPads).

Platform-specific details:
- OS: Darwin (macOS 11+ Big Sur and later on Apple Silicon, iOS 14+, iPadOS 14+)
- Architecture: ARM64 / AArch64 (Apple Silicon — M-series and A-series)
- Syscall convention: BSD-style with X16 = syscall number (NOT X8 like Linux arm64)
- Register usage: X16 (syscall#), X0-X7 (args 1-8), stack (args 9+)
- Syscall instruction: "svc #0x80" (Darwin uses 0x80; Linux arm64 uses #0)
- BSD class mask: 0x2000000 OR'd into X16 to flag a BSD-class trap
- Error convention: carry flag (C) set on error; X0 holds errno when C=1,
  or the result when C=0. Linux arm64 instead returns -errno directly in X0.

Darwin ARM64 Syscall Convention:
- X16: Syscall number (unlike Linux which uses X8)
- X0-X7: Arguments 1-8 (same as AAPCS64 function calling convention)
- Stack: Arguments 9+ (16-byte aligned per Apple ARM64 ABI)
- X0: Return value (can be negative for errors; C flag set on error)

BSD Syscalls vs Mach Syscalls:
- BSD syscalls: Positive numbers (1, 3, 4, 5, etc.) - POSIX-compatible
- Mach syscalls: Negative numbers (used for Mach kernel services such as
  mach_absolute_time, thread_policy_set, host_processor_info)
- This implementation focuses on BSD syscalls (POSIX interface). Where a
  POSIX operation has no BSD syscall equivalent (e.g. getcwd, clock_gettime
  monotonic, sched_getaffinity), the appropriate SYS_* constant either
  returns -1 (sentinel for "use libc bridge") or aliases to the closest
  BSD syscall with full @Reasoning documentation.

IMPORTANT: Darwin syscall numbers are more stable than Windows but can still
vary between macOS versions. These numbers are for macOS 10.13+ (High Sierra)
through current releases; the Apple Silicon transition (macOS 11 Big Sur,
November 2020) did NOT change the BSD syscall numbering.

Sources:
- XNU `bsd/kern/syscalls.master` (XNU 8020.x / macOS 13 Ventura tree)
- Apple "ARM64 Function Calling Convention" (developer.apple.com)
- Apple TN2124 "Mac OS X Debugging Magic"
- POSIX.1-2017
:End Note

Note:
============================================================================
BSD SYSCALL NUMBER CONSTANTS
============================================================================
These are BSD-style syscall numbers for macOS ARM64
Source: XNU kernel syscalls.master file
:End Note

Process called "darwin_arm64_SYS_EXIT" returns Integer:
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Darwin does not provide a distinct exit_group syscall. POSIX `_exit(2)` (BSD
syscall #1) terminates the entire process group atomically on Darwin because
the kernel's process model treats `exit` as a whole-task teardown — Mach task
exit cascades to every thread in the task. Linux distinguishes between
`exit` (single thread) and `exit_group` (all threads), but on Darwin the
single `exit` syscall fulfills both semantics. We therefore alias
SYS_EXIT_GROUP to SYS_EXIT=1 so cross-platform callers obtain the correct
"terminate all threads" behavior without conditional code.
Source: XNU bsd/kern/kern_exit.c proc_exit() ; Apple Developer "exit(2)".
@End Reasoning

Process called "darwin_arm64_SYS_EXIT_GROUP" returns Integer:
    Return 1
End Process

