@Reasoning
Darwin does not expose a public BSD syscall number for `getcwd`. On Linux
the corresponding interface is syscall 79 (x86_64) / 17 (arm64), but XNU's
`syscalls.master` lists no `getcwd` entry — the user-space `getcwd(3)`
function in libsystem walks the vnode chain via the private
`__getattrlist` / F_GETPATH paths and may also use the
`PROC_PIDPATHINFO_VNODE` proc_info(2) channel (syscall 336). For
cross-platform code that issues a raw `SYS_GETCWD` syscall, the only
correct answer is -1 (unsupported), which signals the dispatcher to fall
back to the libc bridge (`__getcwd` via libsystem_c) or to query the
working directory through `proc_info`. We do NOT return 336 (PROC_INFO)
here because that syscall has a completely different argument shape
(pid, flavor, arg, buffer, buffersize) than the POSIX getcwd(buf, size)
contract — substituting it would silently corrupt callers.
Source: XNU bsd/kern/syscalls.master (no `getcwd` entry); Apple
libsystem_c getcwd.c; XNU bsd/sys/proc_info.h proc_pidinfo flavors.
@End Reasoning

Process called "darwin_arm64_SYS_GETCWD" returns Integer:
    Return -1
End Process

