@Reasoning
Darwin does not expose a `brk(2)` system call. The historical Unix heap-break
interface was removed from the BSD syscall table when XNU moved to the Mach
virtual memory subsystem: heap growth on Darwin is handled exclusively via
`mmap(MAP_ANON|MAP_PRIVATE)` regions and `vm_allocate` Mach traps, not via
data-segment break manipulation. Returning -1 here is the canonical sentinel
for "syscall not supported on this platform"; any caller that requests
SYS_BRK on Darwin must fall back to MMAP-based allocation (which is the
correct allocator strategy on Darwin anyway — `malloc` itself uses
`vm_allocate` + `mmap`, not `brk`).
Source: XNU bsd/kern/syscalls.master (no `brk` entry); Apple TN2124
"Mac OS X Debugging Magic" §heap notes; libmalloc magazine_malloc.c.
@End Reasoning

Process called "darwin_arm64_SYS_BRK" returns Integer:
    Return -1
End Process

