    Return 116
End Process

@Reasoning
Darwin does not provide a BSD-level `clock_gettime` syscall — the POSIX
`clock_gettime(3)` interface added in macOS 10.12 is implemented purely in
libsystem_c on top of (a) `gettimeofday` (BSD syscall 116) for wall-clock
sources and (b) `mach_absolute_time()` + `mach_timebase_info()` (Mach
traps, not BSD syscalls) for monotonic / raw / process-CPU sources.
Linux maps `clock_gettime` to syscall 228 (x86_64) / 113 (arm64). On
Darwin the correct fallback for the wall-clock case (`CLOCK_REALTIME`)
is `gettimeofday` = 116, so we return 116 as a semantic surrogate. For
`CLOCK_MONOTONIC` / `CLOCK_MONOTONIC_RAW` the dispatcher must instead
call Mach `mach_absolute_time` via the Mach trap interface (negative
syscall #-3, executed through `svc #0x80` with X16 < 0). High-level
wrappers should branch on `clk_id` and route monotonic queries to Mach.
Source: XNU bsd/kern/syscalls.master; libsystem_c gettime.c;
Apple Technical Q&A QA1398 "Mach Absolute Time Units".
@End Reasoning

