@Reasoning
Darwin has no `brk(2)` syscall (see SYS_BRK reasoning block above). This
wrapper exists to fulfill the 66-proc cross-platform API surface so that
caller code can write `darwin_arm64_syscall_brk(addr)` portably; on Darwin the call
returns -1 (the sentinel returned by SYS_BRK) which signals the caller to
fall back to MMAP-based heap allocation. Note that syscall_1 will still
be invoked with -1 as the syscall number — the ORR with the BSD class
mask (0x2000000) produces a kernel-level invalid syscall code and the
kernel returns -1/ENOSYS, preserving error semantics. Callers SHOULD
test the SYS_BRK return value via `is_error` before issuing this wrapper
to avoid the unnecessary trap.
@End Reasoning

Process called "darwin_arm64_syscall_brk" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Adjust program break (unsupported on Darwin — returns -1)
    Let syscall_num be darwin_arm64_SYS_BRK()
    Return darwin_arm64_syscall_1(syscall_num, addr)
End Process

