Process called "darwin_arm64_syscall_ioctl" takes fd as Integer, cmd as Integer, arg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Dispatcher-API entry-point for POSIX ioctl(2) on Darwin ARM64.
    SYS_ioctl is 54 (Darwin XNU bsd/kern/syscalls.master, shared
    Mach/BSD personality entry 54 — same number as Darwin x86_64
    because XNU keeps a single BSD syscall table across architectures).
    Three-arg shape (fd, request, argp). The arm64 calling convention
    uses x0-x2 for arguments and x16 for the syscall number, with svc
    #0x80 as the syscall instruction.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Composes the syscall by calling darwin_arm64_SYS_IOCTL() (returns
    54) and darwin_arm64_syscall_3(54, fd, cmd, arg). The arm64 svc
    #0x80 path loads 54 into x16, fd into x0, cmd into x1, arg into
    x2, then invokes the kernel; x0 holds the result on return.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) dispatch in XNU — one FD-table lookup and a driver vtable
    jump. Apple Silicon Macs handle the svc #0x80 transition through
    the secure firmware layer; the cost is comparable to but slightly
    higher than Linux's bare syscall instruction. Batch related ioctl
    calls where possible.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    XNU validates fd against the per-process FD table and dispatches
    cmd through the device's fileops.fo_ioctl vtable. arg, if a
    pointer, is dereferenced by the kernel with the structure size
    implied by cmd; callers must size the buffer to match. Apple's
    sandbox profile and entitlement system may intercept ioctl(2)
    for unprivileged or sandboxed processes — callers should expect
    EPERM in restricted contexts.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let syscall_num be darwin_arm64_SYS_IOCTL()
    Return darwin_arm64_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, cmd, arg)
End Process

